body:
The script invokes a custom derive as:

```rust
#[derive(Problem)]
pub struct S1($crate::Unit);
```

The custom derive takes the input and replaces the `S1` token with `S2`, leaving the rest of the tokens untouched. `S1` compiles successfully, correctly referring to `repro_dispatch::Unit` even though the top-level crate has renamed its import of `repro_dispatch`. But `S2` fails to compile with the following error:

```
error[E0433]: failed to resolve. Maybe a missing `extern crate repro_dispatch;`?
```

Originally reported as https://github.com/serde-rs/serde/issues/1305.

---

rustc 1.28.0-nightly (4ecf12bf0 2018-06-02)
Repro script:

```bash
#!/bin/sh

cargo new --lib repro
cargo new --lib repro_dispatch
cargo new --lib repro_derive

echo >repro/src/lib.rs '
#[macro_use]
extern crate repro_dispatch as rename;

#[macro_use]
extern crate repro_derive;

problem!();
'

echo >>repro/Cargo.toml '
repro_dispatch = { path = "../repro_dispatch" }
repro_derive = { path = "../repro_derive" }
'

echo >repro_dispatch/src/lib.rs '
pub struct Unit;

#[macro_export]
macro_rules! problem {
    () => {
        #[derive(Problem)]
        pub struct S1($crate::Unit);
    }
}
'

echo >repro_derive/src/lib.rs '
#![feature(proc_macro)]

extern crate proc_macro;
use proc_macro::{Ident, Span, TokenStream, TokenTree};

#[proc_macro_derive(Problem)]
pub fn derive(input: TokenStream) -> TokenStream {
    // Input: pub struct S1($crate::Unit);
    // Output: pub struct S2($crate::Unit);

    let mut tts = input.into_iter().collect::<Vec<_>>();
    tts[2] = TokenTree::Ident(Ident::new("S2", Span::call_site()));
    tts.into_iter().collect()
}
'

echo >>repro_derive/Cargo.toml '
[lib]
proc-macro = true
'

cargo build --manifest-path repro/Cargo.toml
```
